definition.value: A methanesulfonate ester resulting from the formal condensation of methanesulfonic acid with ethanol.
A member of the class of N-nitrosoureas that is urea in which one of the nitrogens is substituted by ethyl and nitroso groups.
An aliphatic sulfide in which the sulfur atom is bonded to at least one ethyl group.
A fatty acid ester that is the ethyl ester of 3-hydroxyhexanoic acid.
A member of the class of  phenothiazines that is 10H-phenothiazine substituted by a 3-[4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperazin-1-yl]propyl group at the nitogen atom and an acetyl group at position 2.

Amfenac in which the the hydrogen at the 4 position of the benzoyl group is substituted by bromine. It is used for the management of ocular pain and treatment of postoperative inflammation in patients who have undergone cataract extraction. It was withdrawn from the US market in 1998, following concerns over off-label abuse and hepatic failure.
A maleate salt obtained by combining acetophenazine with two molar equivalents of maleic acid.

Any vitamin that dissolves in fats and are stored in body tissues. Unlike the water-soluble vitamins, they are stored in the body for long periods of time and generally pose a greater risk for toxicity when consumed in excess.
An aliphatic alcohol consisting of a chain of 3 to greater than 27 carbon atoms. Fatty alcohols may be saturated or unsaturated and may be branched or unbranched.
A fatty-acyl group is a group formed by loss of OH from the carboxy group of a fatty acid.
A member of the class of  acetophenones that is 1-phenylethanone substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4 and methoxy groups at positions 3 and 5.
A member of the class of flavonoid with a 2-aryl-1-benzopyran-4-one (2-arylchromen-4-one) skeleton and its substituted derivatives.
A member of the class of  fluorenes carrying an oxo substituent at position 9.
An ortho-fused polycyclic arene in which the skeleton is composed of two benzene rings ortho-fused to cyclopentane.
A haloalkane that is an alkane in which at least one hydrogen atom has been replaced by a fluorine atom.
An organofluorine compound that consists of an amino acid substituted by a fluoro group.
A substituted aniline carrying an additional fluoro substituent on the benzene ring.
Any benzoic acid carrying at least one fluoro substituent on the benzene ring. Fluorobenzoic acids are important intermediates in the synthesis of antibacterial drugs.
Any member of the class of benzoyl-CoAs having fluorobenzoyl as the aroyl substituent.
Amides with the general formula R(1)R(2)NCHO (R(1) and R(2) can be H).
Any member of the class of indanones in which a hydrogen attached to carbon in the indanone skeleton has been replaced by a formyl group.
A glyco-amino acid consisting of a D-fructosyl residue attached to the epsilon-amino group of L-lysine.
A 1-O-acetylmaltose in which the anomeric centre at the reducing end has alpha-configuration.
